'''David Bruce "Dave" Goldberg''' (October 2, 1967&nbsp;<U+2013> May 1, 2015) was an American entrepreneur and Silicon Valley executive. He was the founder of [[LAUNCH Media]] and the CEO of [[SurveyMonkey]].  He was married to [[Sheryl Sandberg]], [[COO]] of [[Facebook]].

==Early life and education==
Goldberg was born in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]] on October 2, 1967.<ref name="WP obit">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/david-goldberg-executive-of-online-questionnaire-service-dies-at-47/2015/05/02/a3ded996-f112-11e4-8abc-d6aa3bad79dd_story.html|title=David Goldberg, 47, SurveyMonkey CEO, Sandberg Husband, Dies|last=Coppola|first=Gabrielle|first2=Sarah|last2=Frier|date=May 2, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref> His mother Paula Goldberg is co-founder and executive director of the Pacer Center and his father, Mel Goldberg (1942-1998) was associate dean and professor at the [[William Mitchell College of Law]].<ref name="WP obit" /> He interned at the Minneapolis ''[[Star Tribune]]'' newspaper while in high school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsj.com/articles/david-goldberg-surveymonkey-ceo-dies-at-age-47-1430672009 |title=Web Executive David Goldberg Dies at Age 47 |publisher=''The Wall Street Journal''|subscription=yes |date=May 3, 2015 |accessdate=May 4, 2015 }}</ref> He graduated from [[Blake School (Minneapolis)|Blake School]] in Minneapolis in 1985,<ref name="Star-Trib">{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/302317551.html|title=David Goldberg, Silicon Valley CEO with deep ties to Minneapolis, dies at 47|date=May 3, 2015|work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune|accessdate=May 3, 2015}}</ref> and graduated ''magna cum laude'' from [[Harvard University]] in 1989, majoring in history and government.<ref name=nytimes/> Dave was an avid [[Minnesota Vikings]] fan throughout his life. <ref>https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/remembering-dave-goldberg-ultimate-mensch-adam-grant</ref>

==Career==
Goldberg worked for [[Bain & Company]] for two years after graduating from college. He had planned to attend law school but instead joined [[Capitol Records]], where he served as director of marketing strategy and new business development.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swisher|first1=Kara|title=Former Yahoo Music Exec Dave Goldberg to Head SurveyMonkey|url=http://allthingsd.com/20090420/former-yahoo-music-exec-dave-goldberg-to-head-survey-monkey/|accessdate=4 May 2015|publisher=All Things D|date=April 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=businessinsider>{{cite news|last1=Bort|first1=Julie|title=Dave Goldberg had an incredible life <U+2014> but it wasn't easy|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-incredible-life-of-david-goldberg-2015-5|accessdate=May 3, 2015|work=Business Insider|date=May 2, 2015}}</ref> He founded [[LAUNCH Media]] in 1994, and led it through its acquisition by [[Yahoo!|Yahoo Inc.]] in 2001.<ref name=businessinsider /> He quit Yahoo in 2007 and joined [[Benchmark (venture capital firm)|Benchmark Capital]]. He then joined [[SurveyMonkey]] in 2009.<ref name=nytimes/>

==Personal life==
In 2004, Goldberg married Sheryl Sandberg, with whom he had two children.  They lived in [[Menlo Park, California]].<ref name=nytimes />

==Death and memorials==
On May 1, 2015, Goldberg collapsed at a private beach-front villa near the Four Seasons Resort in [[Punta Mita]], near [[Puerto Vallarta]], Mexico, during a vacation with Sandberg; he died later that day at a hospital in [[Nuevo Vallarta]]. According to the [[Nayarit]] State Prosecutor's Office, Goldberg fell off a [[treadmill]] while exercising at a gym and died after suffering head trauma and blood loss.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite web|last1=Goel|first1=Vindu|last2=Hardy|first2=Quentin|title=Dave Goldberg, Head of Web Survey Company and Half of a Silicon Valley Power Couple, Dies at 47|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/03/business/dave-goldberg-47-surveymonkey-chief-and-sheryl-sandbergs-husband-dies.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goel|first1=Vindu|title=Dave Goldberg, Silicon Valley Executive, Said to Have Died After Exercising|url=http://nyti.ms/1KHa9Yq|work=The New York Times|accessdate=4 May 2015|last2=Archibold|first2=Randal C.}}</ref><ref name="BBCaccident"> {{cite news  
| url=  http://www.bbc.com/news/business-32586657
| title=  Silicon Valley's Dave Goldberg died after gym accident
| publisher=  [[BBC News]]
| date=  May 5, 2015
| accessdate= 
}}  </ref>

Goldberg's brother, Robert Goldberg, in an article written by Tim Bradshaw in [[San Francisco]] for the ''[[Financial Times]]'' that appeared on the website of [[MSN#MSN News|MSN News]], on Saturday, May 2, 2015, described his family's "incredible shock and sadness", in an online post asking well-wishers to post photos and memories to his [[Facebook]] profile page." "In lieu of donations, we want to celebrate his life in a manner that respects the family<U+2019>s privacy as they cope with this tragic, life changing event", Robert Goldberg wrote. Tributes to Mr. Goldberg were posted to social media across the Silicon Valley community. A spokeperson for Facebook said its executives were "heartbroken by this news." [[Mark Zuckerberg]], Facebook<U+2019>s chief executive, said in a post that Mr. Goldberg was "an amazing person and I am glad I got to know him". "One of the truly great people on the planet, Dave was of almost unimaginably remarkable character," said [[Dick Costolo]], [[Twitter]]<U+2019>s chief executive. "One of kindest and most generous friends I<U+2019>ve known," said [[Jeff Weiner]], chief executive of [[LinkedIn]].<ref name=nytimes /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw|first1=Tim|title=Silicon Valley entrepreneur David Goldberg dies|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/technology/silicon-valley-entrepreneur-david-goldberg-dies/ar-BBj5pYB?ocid=ansfinancialtimes11|accessdate=4 May 2015|work=Financial Times|via=MSN.com|date=May 2, 2015}}</ref>

A memorial service for Goldberg was held at [[Stanford Memorial Auditorium]] on the [[Stanford University]] campus on May 5, 2015. The 90-minute service was attended by many members of what ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' described as "the elite of Silicon Valley", as well as [[U2]] frontman [[Bono]], who performed his song "[[One (U2 song)|One]]", and actor [[Ben Affleck]], who had worked with Goldberg on a philanthropy project in Africa.<ref name=FortuneStanford>{{cite news|last1=Lashinsky|title=Tears and laughter at a celebration of Dave Goldberg's life|first1=Adam|url=https://fortune.com/2015/05/05/dave-goldberg-memorial-stanford/|accessdate=May 6, 2015|work=[[Fortune]]|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref>

